2.Tea Productivity: ï‚· The Tea Board had released the September (2016) production data which shows that India lost 44.17 million kg (M.kg) over September 2016 to total 145.83 M.kg. ï‚· North India lost 42.14 M.kg to produce 127.54 M.kg while South India lost 2.03 M.kg to produce 18.29 M.kgâ€, Consequently, our compilation shows that at the end of the first three quarters of 2016, Indiaâ€™s production has fallen to 912.55 M.kg from 923.27 M.kg, marking a marginal fall of 1.16 per centâ€. ï‚· In the ten months, North India lost 25.79 M.kg to produce 737.87 M.kg. Assam continued to top Indiaâ€™s production table despite a lower output this year. The state produced 464.29 M.kg â€“ as much as 23.33 M.kg less than the relevant months of 2016. ï‚· Darjeeling also reported a lower production â€“ 2.07 M.kg against 6.88 M.kg last year.As of 2017, industry sources estimate the countryâ€™s production in the current calendar to be around 1257 M.kg in 2017 â€“ some 10 M.kg less than 2016. ï‚· But in 2017 Indiaâ€™s production had increased to 1,278.83 M.kg from 1,267.36 M.kg in 2016. This increase of 11.47 M.kg marks a marginal growth of 0.91 per cent. North Indian overall output in 2017 dropped to 1,046.42 M.kg from 1,054.51 M.kg due to adverse weather conditions in many months, marking a marginal loss of 0.77 per cent.
